<h2>Common PDF Resize Scenarios</h2>

<h3>Converting US Letter to A4</h3>
<p>
  US Letter (8.5 × 11 inches) and A4 (210 × 297 mm) are close in size but slightly different — Letter is wider and shorter. When converting Letter PDFs for international audiences, resize to A4 so they print correctly on standard European paper.
</p>

<h3>Converting A4 to US Letter</h3>
<p>
  If you receive A4 PDFs but need to print on US Letter paper (common in North America), resizing to Letter prevents the printer from scaling the content or adding unwanted white borders.
</p>

<h3>Converting A3 to A4</h3>
<p>
  Large A3 documents (posters, architectural drawings, spreadsheets) can be resized to A4 for standard printing. The content will be scaled down to half the original size.
</p>

<h3>Standardising mixed-size PDFs</h3>
<p>
  When you merge PDFs from different sources, the pages may have different sizes. Resize all pages to a uniform size before merging for a consistent result.
</p>

<h2>How to Resize a PDF in Adobe Acrobat</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Acrobat Pro.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Print</strong>.</li>
  <li>Select the target paper size from the printer settings.</li>
  <li>Check <strong>Scale</strong> → <strong>Fit</strong> (or custom scale percentage).</li>
  <li>Print to Adobe PDF or "Save as PDF".</li>
</ol>

<p>Alternatively, use <strong>Tools → Edit PDF → More → Crop Pages</strong> to set a custom page size.</p>

<h2>How to Resize a PDF on Mac (Preview)</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Preview.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>File → Print</strong> (Cmd+P).</li>
  <li>Change the paper size to your target (A4, Letter, etc.).</li>
  <li>Enable <strong>Scale to fit page</strong> in the print settings.</li>
  <li>Choose "Save as PDF" as the printer to export instead of printing.</li>
</ol>

<h2>How to Change PDF Page Size in Microsoft Word</h2>

<p>If you have the original Word source document:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>Layout → Size</strong> and choose the target page size (A4 or Letter).</li>
  <li>Adjust margins if needed.</li>
  <li>Re-export as PDF: <strong>File → Save As → PDF</strong>.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Resize vs. Crop vs. Compress — What Is the Difference?</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Resize:</strong> Changes the page dimensions and scales content proportionally to fit — same content, different size</li>
  <li><strong>Crop:</strong> Hides the edges of a page without changing page size or scaling content — useful for removing white margins</li>
  <li><strong>Compress:</strong> Reduces file size without changing page dimensions — optimises internal PDF structure for smaller downloads</li>
</ul>

